The Response of Basal Area Growth of Scots Pine to Thinning: A Longitudinal Analysis of Tree-Specific Series Using a Nonlinear Mixed-Effects Model

Lauri Mehtätalo, Heli Peltola, Antti Kilpeläinen, Veli-Pekka Ikonen
Forest Science, Volume 60, Issue 4, August 2014, Pages 636–644, https://doi.org/10.5849/forsci.13-059
Published:
17 October 2013
Article history
  • PDF
  • Split View
  • Cite
  • Permissions Icon Permissions
  • Share

The growth dynamics of a tree may be affected by different silvicultural treatments of the stand, such as thinning or fertilization. A proper analysis of such effects at the tree level should take into account the nuisance caused by age-driven growth dynamics, the tree- and site-specific growth pattern, and the growth conditions of the calendar year. In this context, we analyzed the growth response of individual Scots pine (Pinus sylvestris L.) trees to thinnings of varying intensity. We first determined basal areas of annual rings from pith to bark at 1.3 m above the stem base for a total of 88 sample trees, based on ring density profiles measured using an X-ray microdensitometer. Second, a linear mixed-effects model prediction with the predicted year and tree effects was subtracted from the annual basal area growths to remove the effects of age and calendar year from the series. In the third stage, these extracted tree-level thinning responses were modeled using a nonlinear mixed-effects model, with parameters for the time needed until the reduced competition can be fully used (reaction time), the full thinning response after the reaction time has elapsed (maximum thinning response), and later gradual decrease of the thinning response. We found that the maximum thinning response was significantly (P < 0.001) affected by thinning intensity, whereas the reaction time was significantly (P = 0.004) affected by the size of the tree before thinning. The thinning response started a slow decrease a few years after the maximum was reached. The observed mechanism of the effects of tree size and thinning intensity on the tree-level response might generalize to other locations and tree species too. The applied method demonstrates the applicability of linear and nonlinear mixed-effects modeling for analysis of the treatment response on individual tree growth and dynamics of the response. A similar approach can be used for analysis of other longitudinal treatment data as well.

thinning response, X-ray densitometry, nonlinear mixed-effect model, longitudinal analysis, crossed random effect, treatment response

In addition to environmental factors such as climate, weather, and site conditions, the growth of forest trees is affected by silvicultural treatments. For example, thinning affects the mean tree-level growth both by accelerating the growth rate of the remaining trees and through selective removal of their competitors. In the remaining trees, increases in radial growth will be the highest in the lower part of the stem (Assmann 1970). However, the removal of trees resulting from thinning will, at least temporarily, decrease the stand level growth because the remaining trees need some time to recover from the past competition before their increased growth compensates for the growth of the removed trees.

The response to a treatment, such as thinning, should be visible in a year-by-year time series of individual tree growth. However, this response is hindered by the nuisance caused by the age-driven growth dynamics, the tree-specific growth pattern, and the year-by-year variation in the growth, which is controlled mainly by the weather of the growing period. If one is interested only in the response to the treatment, these factors are not of interest. A proper analysis should take them into account to better recognize the pure treatment response, but the underlying factors affecting them (e.g., local growth conditions, weather information, or predictors of the deterministic part of the growth function) are not of interest. In particular, the situation differs from those situations in which the underlying factors affecting tree growth are included to build growth models (e.g., Wykoff 1990, Lessard et al. 2001, Burkhart and Tomé 2012). Therefore, methods that in a justified manner model out these effects are sufficient.

One of the most commonly used approaches to account for the nuisance effects is randomization, e.g., in a controlled experiment (e.g., Peltola et al. 2007). However, this approach does not allow a detailed analysis of tree-level dynamics. For a tree-level analysis of thinning response, one might take the difference between observed growth after thinning and growth prediction without thinning (Pukkala et al. 2002) or subtract the mean growth of the tree just before thinning from the observed postthinning growth (Valinger et al. 2000). However, these approaches have several weaknesses. For example, they do not take into account the year-by-year variation caused by weather conditions, or the previously fitted model may be too averaging. In addition, the use of past growth does not take into account the age-driven growth dynamics.

More sophisticated methods to model time series of tree rings have been developed in the field of dendrochronology (e.g., Monseurd 1986), for which the ultimate aim is to find information on past climate using coregistered ring width time series from the past. To extract such information, the commonly used approach includes steps of standardization, prewhitening, and climate modeling of the tree-specific time series (Cook and Kairiukstis 1990). Van Deusen (1989) proposed a one-step model-based approach applying a linear mixed-effects model with crossed random effects. The crossed effects take into account the common effect of weather for the observations of different trees of the region in a given calendar year.

The linear mixed-effects model allows, in principle, modeling of the nuisance effects and the interesting treatment responses in the same model (Mäkinen and Isomäki 2004a, 2004b, Pukkala et al. 2002). The mixed-effects model also allows more detailed modeling of residual variance and inherent autocorrelation (see, e.g., Tasissa and Burkhart 1997, Pinheiro and Bates 2000), leading to more reliable estimates of the treatment responses. However, even though the dynamic response over time can be satisfactorily modeled using a linear mixed-effects model, the parameters of the model do not have biologically meaningful interpretations. The nonlinear mixed-effects model (e.g., Pinheiro and Bates 2000) allows modeling of the response using a nonlinear function, which can be parameterized using meaningful parameters with straightforward interpretations. In addition, testing the effects of different factors on these parameters is possible. However, nonlinear mixed-effects models as implemented in the most widely used statistical packages (R and SAS) do not currently allow crossed random effects.

In this study, we analyzed tree-level thinning responses in the basal area growth of individual trees using tree-level chronologies. Because of the restrictions in the software, the analysis is done in two steps. In the first step, to predict the tree-level growth without thinning, we fitted a linear mixed-effects model with crossed random effects to the growth series not affected by thinning. The model was thereafter used to predict the undisturbed growth, taking into account three factors: the tree-to-tree variation in the level of growth, the age-driven biological growth trend, and the effect of calendar years. The thinning responses resulted from subtraction of the observed growth and this prediction. The second step included modeling of the resulting series of thinning responses using a nonlinear mixed-effects model for longitudinal data (Pinheiro and Bates 2000). The nonlinear model quantified the thinning response with meaningful parameters and allowed testing of the effects of different variables (e.g., thinning intensity and tree diameter before thinning) separately.

Materials and Methods

Experimental Data

The trees used in this study were harvested from a long-term thinning experiment established in 1986 in a naturally regenerated Scots pine stand growing on a site with a relatively poor nutrient supply (Vaccinium site type) in Eastern Finland (62°47′ N and 30°58′ E, 145 m above sea level). The experiment consisted of 10 plots (rectangular 40 × 30 m; 0.12 ha), in which randomized thinning treatments were carried out in the winter of 1986–1987 (Table 1). Each plot was also surrounded by a 10-m buffer zone, which was treated in the same way as the plot. The mean age of the trees at breast height was 27 years at the time of thinning. The initial basal area varied between 20 and 25 m2 ha−1, with the exception of plot 3, which already had a significantly lower basal area (13.2 m2 ha−1) before thinning.

The 10 plots were grouped into four different classes according to the postthinning stand density of plots: I, three plots with 2,942–3,683 trees ha−1 (i.e., very light or no thinning); II, three plots with 1,800–2,383 trees ha−1 (i.e., light thinning, with 19–33% basal area removal); III, two plots with 1,200–1,492 trees ha−1 (i.e., moderate thinning, with 37–45% basal area removal, corresponding best to business-as-usual management), and IV, two plots with 575–850 trees ha−1 (i.e., heavy thinning, with 61–63% basal area removal). The thinning was always performed from below.

In winter 2006–2007, 10 trees were destructively sampled from throughout the size hierarchy in each plot (i.e., three small, four medium-sized, and three large trees from each plot), for a total of 100 sample trees. Cross-sectional discs were cut from each sample tree at a height of 1.3 m (breast height) for further laboratory analyses of past growth. Ring widths from pith to bark were analyzed for each disc, using an ITRAX X-ray microdensitometer (Cox Analytical Systems, Gothenburg, Sweden) at the University of Eastern Finland, School of Forest Sciences. For this purpose, a radial segment from pith to bark in the south direction (5 mm axially and tangentially) was first cut from each sample disc and air-dried to have a moisture content of 12%. Thereafter, the samples were scanned using the ITRAX (with standard X-ray intensity of 30 kV and 35 mA and exposure time of 20 ms), recording X-ray images with a geometrical resolution of 40 measurements per millimeter (cf. Peltola et al. 2007). Using Density software (Bergsten et al. 2001) and Excel macros, the X-ray images were further analyzed to create intraring density profiles for each wood specimen, and based on these profiles, ring widths from pith to bark were determined for each disc.

Out of the 100 felled trees, altogether 88 trees (7–10 trees from each plot) could be used for further data analyses (Table 1) because 12 sample trees had annual rings that were too narrow (<0.3 mm, with <12 measuring points in each ring for ITRAX analyses). In rejected trees, the highest ring density values in particular and also the lowest ring density values were cut from the intraring density profile; thus, density profiles with sufficient quality (>20 measurements per ring needed) for reliable tree ring detection were not provided. We had a total of 18–26 sample trees from each stand density class for further data analyses (Table 1).

Preliminary Tests on Ring Basal Area and Tree Diameter

The annual ring width data, measured using ITRAX, represented the period from 1960 to 2005. However, we used only data after 1982, including a 4-year prethinning period (1983–1986) for estimating the tree-specific effects in growth rate and the 18-year postthinning period (1987–2005) for actual analysis of the thinning responses. The 4-year period was assumed to be sufficient to estimate the pretreatment tree-level effects on tree growth, whereas a longer prethinning period would have required a more complex model for the undisturbed growth without a significant advantage for the estimation of tree effects. The differences between thinning treatments in average pre- and postthinning ring basal areas and dbh for years 1986 and 2005 were computed and tested by using one-way analysis of variance and Tukey's tests to determine the effect of postthinning density on the average thinning responses. These analyses were done separately for smaller (dbh <85 mm) and larger (dbh ≥85 mm) trees, the dbh of 85 mm being the approximate median dbh of the data set.

Extracting Thinning Responses Using a Multilevel Mixed-Effects Model

To quantify the pure annual tree-level thinning responses, the effects of tree age, annual weather, and tree were removed from the data by using a model that predicts the tree-level growth without thinning. For this purpose, we modeled the sample tree data from unthinned sample plots with a model that included a smooth age trend and tree- and year-level random effects. The unthinned sample plots were the control plots (i.e., plots 1, 2, and 9) over the whole time series and the other plots up to the year of thinning. Such a data set included information about the age-driven growth trend over the whole range of tree ages, the tree effects of all trees (including those of the thinned plots), and the year effects of all calendar years before and after thinning. The following linear mixed-effects model was used
where ln(ykt) is the logarithmic ring basal area for tree k in year t, f(Tkt) is the average age trend of the basal area growth without thinning, uk is a normally distributed random effect for tree k (tree effect), vt is a normally distributed random effect for calendar year t (year effect), and ekt is the normally distributed residual for tree k at year t. Logarithmic transformation was used for the response because such formulation provided homogeneous residuals and good fit of the above model, with no need for additional random effects. The tree effects include the variation caused by unspecified tree-level factors (e.g., small-scale site variation). This effect is common for all observations of a given tree at different years. The year effect includes the unspecified climatic effects of a given calendar year and is common to the rings of different trees for a given calendar year. An additional plot-level random effect was also tested, but it did not significantly improve the model (P > 0.05).
The age trend f(Tkt) was modeled using a restricted cubic spline (Harrell 2001, Gort et al. 2011). The spline is a smooth, flexible curve, consisting of pieces of third-order polynomials between prespecified knots tj, j = 1, …, J. The flexibility is controlled by the number of knots, which are placed within the range of predictor Tkt. Using J knots, the spline can be expressed as

Using a Bayesian information measure as the criterion, three knots placed at tree ages 22, 31, and 41 years were found sufficient to model the age trend. This small number of knots was sufficient because the growth of the trees from the control plots was fairly smooth within the age range of the data. The model was fitted using the lmer function of R package lme4 (R Development Core Team 2010).

Because the model-fitting data included observations for each tree and calendar year, we had predictions of the random effects for all trees in the data set and all calendar years after thinning. Based on this model, we could make predictions of undisturbed growth for the trees of the thinned plots after the thinning in 1986. These predictions account for the age trend, tree effects, and weather related calendar year effects for each year but assume no thinning treatment. Consequently, by subtracting these predictions from the true observed values, we extracted the estimated thinning responses for all individual trees of the thinned plots after thinning,

(2006). The thinning responses were computed for all trees of the thinned plots after the thinning year. Examples of these thinning responses are shown in the right panel of Figure 2.

Nonlinear Mixed-Effects Modeling of Thinning Responses

By plotting the thinning responses (Equation 4) against the time after thinning, we can observe a reaction time of a few years before the thinning response levels out at its maximum. Thereafter, a slight decrease in the thinning response can be visually detected. The S-shaped increasing trend right after the thinning seems fairly symmetric. Based on these observations, we modeled the thinning response using two components: an increasing, S-shaped logistic curve for the increasing growth until the reaction time has elapsed and the maximum thinning response has been achieved and a linear, decreasing trend thereafter.

The logistic curve is one of the simplest and most widely used models for S-shaped, symmetric responses. The general three-parameter logistic model (e.g., Pinheiro and Bates 2000, p. 519) allows any starting point for the reaction. We restricted the starting point to the year of thinning and reparameterized the scale parameter as the reaction time, which reduced the number of parameters to 2. However, because of the tail behavior of the logistic curve, we technically restricted the tree to already have 2% of the maximum thinning response at the year of thinning and 98% of the maximum response at the year of maximum response. However, we interpret these values as 0 and maximum responses, respectively. As a result, the thinning response dkt for tree k in year t was expressed using the following two-parameter nonlinear mixed-effects model
where xkt is the time after thinning (years), Mk is the maximum thinning response after the reaction time Rk, and D is a coefficient describing the decreasing growth trend, which is fixed to start 7 years after the thinning (Figure 1). The selection of the fixed starting point was based on the graphs, and small changes on it had no significant effects on the results. The estimation of this effect as an additional parameter was also considered but, as one might expect, the estimation of this parameter led to convergence problems because the decreasing trend in the thinning response was so weak.

The residual variance was modeled by
where σ2, δ1, and δ2 are the parameters of the variance function. In addition, the first-order autoregressive correlation structure for the residuals for a given tree at successive years was found sufficient to model the temporal autocorrelation of the residuals
where δ3 is the parameter and Δ is the time lag for the two observations. The motivation for proper modeling of the variance and temporal autocorrelation of the residuals arose from the resulting increase in reliability of inference based on the model, especially that of the fixed coefficients.

The model was first fitted by assuming parameters Mk and Rk to have fixed means and random, bivariate normal tree effects. However, part of the variation in these tree-level random effects might be explained by thinning treatments or tree diameter before thinning. To explore this potential dependency, the tree effects of both parameters were predicted, and their dependence on the thinning treatment and tree diameter were explored graphically. Whenever any potential dependence was indicated by the graphs, the predictor was incorporated into the model, and the resulting more advanced model was fitted. The Wald test, as suggested by Pinheiro and Bates (2000), was used to iteratively test whether the more advanced model was significantly better (P < 0.05) than a simpler one, until no improvement was possible.

Results

Before the thinning, the average ring basal area and dbh of sample trees did not differ significantly (P > 0.05) between stand density classes (Table 2). However, there was a slightly significant difference in ring basal area for small trees (i.e., the prethinning basal area growth of small trees was significantly higher in treatment IV than in treatment III). After thinning, significant differences among treatments were detected in the dbh of small trees and in the ring basal areas of the trees from both diameter classes. Thus, all trees showed a reaction to the thinning, but the reactions (in absolute terms) of large trees exposed to the most intensive thinning treatments were the strongest.

The data, which did not include observations from the thinned plots after the thinning year, showed a total variation of 0.421 in the logarithmic ring basal area. Of this variation, the age trend of model 1 explained 13%, the tree effect explained 68%, the year effect explained 5%, and the remaining 14% was unexplained residual variance (Table 3).

Growth of the trees from the thinned plots without thinning was predicted using the fitted mixed-effects model, and subtracted from the observed growths to extract the thinning responses. Comparison of the raw basal area growths (Figure 2, left panel) and the extracted thinning responses (Figure 2, right panel) showed that the removal of the nuisance effects made the thinning responses more clearly visible. A trend line fitted to the thinning response data showed a gradually increasing thinning response that levels out between years 1990 and 1995 and more or less remains at a constant level until the end of the follow-up period, with a slight indication about a decreasing trend.

The nonlinear model based on logistic function (Equation 5) was fitted to the data of extracted thinning responses by assuming tree-level random parameters for both Mk and Rk. Tree-level effects were also tried for parameter D, but this did not significantly improve the model (P > 0.05). The predicted random effects of the basic model (Equation 5) were found to be associated with thinning treatment and standardized diameter. In particular, we found a statistically significant association between the random effect of Mk and the thinning treatment (Figure 3). In addition, the graphs indicated potential correlations between the random effect of Rk and diameters before both thinning and treatment. However, after trying several different models and comparing them using the Akaike information criterion, Wald tests, and likelihood ratio tests (Pinheiro and Bates 2000), we found that the maximum thinning response could be significantly explained by treatment (P < 0.0001), whereas the reaction time could be significantly explained by tree diameter before thinning (P = 0.0055). Therefore, the parameters Mk and Rk (Equation 5) were further rewritten as
where μ0, …, μ2 and ρ0, ρ1 are the fixed parameters, T2 and T3 are indicator variables indicating moderate and heavy thinning, respectively, mk and rk are tree-level bivariate normal random effects, and zk is the standardized diameter of tree k at the year before thinning. The standardized diameter before thinning, computed by standardizing the observed dbh at the year 1986, was used instead of the raw diameter to remove the correlation between the estimates of ρ0 and ρ1 and to provide meaningful interpretations for ρ0 and ρ1.

The fixed parameters have the following interpretations: μ0 specifies the average maximum thinning response for light thinning and μ1 and μ2 specify the differences for moderate and heavy thinning compared with light thinning. The parameter ρ0 is the mean reaction time over the trees, and ρ1 is the change in the reaction time caused by a difference of 1 SD in tree diameter; therefore, the largest trees have an average reaction time of roughly ρ0 − 1.96ρ1 and the smallest trees of ρ0 + 1.96ρ1.

The full nonlinear model (Equation 5) with the submodels 6 and 7 for parameters Mk and Rk was fitted to the data of extracted thinning responses (Table 4). The estimated maximum thinning responses for light, moderate, and heavy thinning were 91, 182, and 259 mm2/year, respectively. The average reaction time was 5.5 years. The reaction time did not vary significantly among thinning treatments, but it was shorter for large trees than for small ones, such that an increase of 1 SD in diameter decreased the reaction time by 1.4 years. Therefore, the mean reaction time varied from 2.8 years (largest trees) to 8.2 years (smallest trees). After 7 years, there was also a slight time-dependent decrease of 3.2 mm2/year2 in the thinning response, indicating that it decreased slightly (P = 0.0038) after the reaction time had elapsed. However, this effect was quite marginal compared with the observed maximum thinning responses of 91–259 mm2/year.

The residuals of the model increased with respect to the predicted thinning response, but that variation was successfully modeled using the applied variance function so that the graph of standardized residuals (not shown) did not show signs of heteroscedasticity. In addition, the residuals had a strong temporal autocorrelation of 0.59, which was successfully modeled using the AR(1) process.

Discussion

Modeling Approach

The mixed-effects models provided a sound approach to clear the tree-specific basal area growth time series from the nuisance effects of tree age, unspecified tree-specific factors, and climatic/weather (calendar year) effects and longitudinally model the consequent pure treatment responses of individual Scots pine trees. In our study, the increase in the thinning response right after the thinning was parameterized by two different parameters, the reaction time and maximum thinning response (Figure 1), which were further explained by thinning treatment and tree diameter before thinning. Furthermore, the decreasing thinning response was modeled by a linear trend starting 7 years after thinning. The main advantage of the nonlinear longitudinal modeling approach over an alternative linear mixed-effects model was the possibility for more detailed analysis of the thinning response dynamics and the meaningful testing and interpretation of the parameters. Such a model could improve our understanding of the dynamics of the response, as demonstrated by the discussion that follows in the next subsection. Furthermore, sophisticated modeling of variance and autocorrelation of the residuals was also possible, thus improving the reliability of the inference on the fixed effects.

A drawback of the nonlinear modeling approach was the need to do the modeling in two steps. A natural next step in our modeling work is to write the models of the two modeling steps in a single model with a linear component for the unthinned growth and an additive nonlinear thinning response. Such a model would have made better use of the data than the two-step procedure. However, such analysis would have required a nonlinear mixed-effects model with crossed random effects. Unfortunately, the widely used software programs (e.g., R, SAS, and SPSS) do not currently provide tools for fitting such models.

An alternative to the nonlinear model for the thinning response is a linear model with transformations in the predictors that allow the shape shown in Figure 1. For example, a high-order polynomial or a similar spline as in model 1 (see Equation 2) could have been used as well. Such a model could have provided a fit as good as that for the nonlinear model of this study. The tests on the model should also have been even more reliable because they do not need linear approximations for the likelihood as do the tests for the nonlinear model. Furthermore, a linear mixed-effects model for the thinning response would have allowed pooling of the two models into one single model. However, the parameters of the linear model would not have had clear interpretations. Our main target was to better understand and formally test how stand density and tree size affect the thinning response of single trees. Therefore, even though the linear one-step model could have provided the benefits described above, the nonlinear modeling was a better tool for this study.

The decrease in the thinning response after the reaction time was modeled in our work by a linear trend, starting 7 years after the reaction time. The starting point was given as fixed because the decreasing trend was so weak in our data that a two-parameter model for it showed problems in model fitting. We also tried other fixed starting points, as well as starting right after the reaction time. The other fixed starting points did not make a significant difference in our model, whereas using reaction time as the starting point mixed the interpretation of this parameter both as the reaction time and as the starting time of the gradual decrease of the response.

The assumed linear decrease for the thinning response was sufficient for the 18-year follow-up period of our data, but it is naturally not sufficient for longer follow-up periods because it allows the response to become negative. Some trials on a more complex form of this component were also done (e.g., some asymptotically decreasing functions), but they were unsuccessful because of a follow-up time that was too short compared with the time needed for the full disappearance of the thinning response. In fact, we hypothesize that the thinning response of individual trees could remain positive in our thinning plots until canopy closure occurs again, revealing increased competition between neighboring trees for growth resources (light, water, and nutrients).

This work demonstrated that the mixed-effects models may be justified for two different reasons, i.e., prediction and inference. In the first step of the analysis, the linear mixed-effects model was fitted to predict the undisturbed growth of the trees in the thinned plots. This approach allowed prediction of the undisturbed growth that is based on only a small number of pretreatment measurements and is unbiased over the calendar years and trees. On the other hand, a sophisticated model for residual autocorrelation was not necessary because the inference on the parameter estimates was not so important. In the second step, the main motivation for mixed-effects model was inference: the random effects together with the variance function and the model for residual autocorrelation parameterized the structure of the data in such a way that the inference on the fixed parameters was reliable. On the other hand, predictions of random effects of this model were not of as much interest as in the first step of the analysis.

Dynamics of The Thinning Response

The linear mixed-effects model with crossed effects could explain 86% of the total variance in the logarithmic basal area growth of Scots pine trees in the unthinned sample plots (i.e., the control treatment for the whole period and thinned plots before the thinning). Of the explained variation, tree-to-tree variation contributed the major proportion (68% of the total variation), followed by the age trend (13%) and year-to-year variation (5%). However, because the sample plots were roughly of the same age, the age trend and year effects may have been somewhat mixed. Had the trees been younger, the age trend would have played a much more important role because the age-driven growth trend is most variable at young ages (e.g., Gort et al. 2011).

As expected by the previous studies (e.g., Valinger 1992, Ruha and Varmola 1997, Hasenauer et al. 1997, Pukkala et al. 1998, Montero et al. 2001, Peltola et al. 2002, 2007, Mäkinen et al. 2005), the thinning intensity and tree size increased the average thinning responses over the whole 18-year postthinning period (Table 2). However, the longitudinal analysis of the tree-specific series of thinning responses revealed the different mechanisms behind the thinning dynamics. The thinning intensity mostly affected the maximum thinning response, whereas tree size mostly affected the reaction time. Although visually detectable relationships were also observed between tree size and maximum thinning response and between treatment and reaction time (Figure 3), these relationships were not statistically significant in our final model (P > 0.05). In addition, there was much remaining variation in the tree-level responses to thinning that could not be explained by thinning treatments or tree size.

An increase in the maximum thinning response to thinning intensity can be naturally explained by the reduced competition for growth resources between the remaining trees in a stand after thinning. Similarly, the effect of tree size on reaction time can be explained by the time needed for a tree to increase its crown (needle) area, affecting the growth rate of a tree (Medhurst and Beadle 2001, 2005). In our study, the reaction time was clearly shorter for larger trees than for smaller ones, ranging from 3 to 8 years. Scots pine usually has three to four needle age classes in southern Finland (Sarvas 1961). Therefore, the reaction time for the largest trees is roughly as long as the time needed to renew all the needle classes after thinning.

Our analysis confirmed and quantified the slow response of basal area growth to thinning in coniferous trees. Similar results have been graphically reported before (e.g., Jonsson 1995, Tasissa and Burkhart 1997, Valinger et al. 2000) but without explicit quantification and statistical testing. After the reaction time, only a slight decrease in the thinning response over the 18-year postthinning period was observed in our study. Some previous studies (e.g., Jonsson 1995, Ikonen et al. 2006) have reported a larger decrease, but this may be an artifact explained by the fact that the analysis was based on radial growth (ring width). Because of the increase in circumference, similar basal area growth implies larger diameter growth for small trees than for large trees and vice versa. In principle, our results showing only a slow decrease in the thinning response over time is logical, as one could expect that the thinning response, especially in lower parts of the bole, will last until the free crown space is completely fulfilled.

Our results indicate that most trees can eventually reach rather similar thinning responses on basal area growth over the 18-year study period, even though it takes a longer time for the smallest trees. Therefore, the decreased total growth rate after thinning should last longer after thinning from above than after thinning from below. However, maximum thinning responses after the reaction time should not show large differences.

Conclusions

This work demonstrated the good applicability of the linear and nonlinear mixed-effects modeling approach for analyses on the response of individual tree growth on a treatment. Our approach could be applied in other circumstances and for other treatments, too. The empirical results showed that the maximum thinning response was affected by thinning intensity, whereas the reaction time was affected significantly by the size of the tree before thinning. The thinning response also decreased slowly after the maximum response was reached. The observed mechanism on the effects of tree size and thinning intensity on the tree-level response might generalize to other locations and tree species, too. However, because our data represented only one thinning experiment and some very suppressed sample trees (mainly from control and light thinning treatments) had to be removed from the analysis because of undetectable narrow rings, the numerical estimates of the thinning effect should not be generalized.

Jarmo Pennala is also thanked for assistance with X-ray measurements. The support provided by the University of Eastern Finland, School of Forest Sciences, is gratefully acknowledged.
